{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477805"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:05:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:05:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14758"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14758"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.01,0.23,0.02,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7449"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62689"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7449"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14758"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48137"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2121"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6054"},{"type":"tags","id":"6292"},{"type":"tags","id":"7399"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18228"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18644"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19184"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19235"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62689"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn eight-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department after falling onto an outstretched hand while playing in the playground one hour ago. He complains of severe pain in his right elbow. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 105/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His right elbow is grossly swollen and deformed. The skin is intact but tense. X-rays are shown below (image 1, image 2)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most at risk of injury in this fracture pattern?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Brachial artery","Basilic vein","Radial artery","Cephalic vein","Profunda brachii artery"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a Gartland type III supracondylar fracture of the humerus, characterised by complete displacement with no cortical contact.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebrachial artery\u003C/strong\u003E is the most commonly injured vessel in displaced supracondylar fractures. The artery can be stretched, compressed, or lacerated by the sharp proximal fragment as it displaces anteriorly. Injury typically presents with decreased or absent distal pulses, poor perfusion, and prolonged capillary refill time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasilic vein\u003C/strong\u003E runs more medially and is less commonly injured in these fractures due to its location and the collateral venous drainage available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial artery\u003C/strong\u003E branches from the brachial artery distal to the typical fracture site and is therefore less commonly directly injured by the fracture fragments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecephalic vein\u003C/strong\u003E runs laterally in the arm and is relatively protected from injury in supracondylar fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprofunda brachii artery\u003C/strong\u003E branches more proximally in the arm and runs posteriorly with the radial nerve, making it less susceptible to injury in these fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis fracture pattern requires urgent reduction and fixation. Regular vascular observations including pulse, perfusion, and capillary refill time are essential both before and after treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The brachial artery is the most commonly injured vessel in Gartland type III supracondylar fractures due to its anterior location.","Vascular assessment including pulses, perfusion, and capillary refill is critical in supracondylar fractures.","Gartland type III fractures are completely displaced with no cortical contact and require urgent reduction and fixation."],"references":["Kumar V, Singh A. Fracture Supracondylar Humerus: A Review. J Clin Diagn Res. 2016 Dec;10(12):RE01-RE06. doi: 10.7860/JCDR/2016/21647.8942. Epub 2016 Dec 1. PMID: 28208961; PMCID: PMC5296534."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48137"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14758"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21115"},{"type":"media","id":"21116"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21115"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/vjTiWbyueg4pKkuGYAGesJOTjpHgye.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/vjTiWbyueg4pKkuGYAGesJOTjpHgye.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1207}},{"type":"media","id":"21116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21116"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/g9KrbHAwlY1T7eaQwY6H2wOEGU6Z6H.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/g9KrbHAwlY1T7eaQwY6H2wOEGU6Z6H.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":859}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/ite